<span id="xiv.iii.lviii-p1"></span> <span id="page_392">p. 392</span>
<span id="xiv.iii.lviii-Page_392"></span><span class="c4"><span
id="xiv.iii.lviii-p1.1"></span>Canon LVII.</span>

<span id="xiv.iii.lviii-p2"></span><span class="sc"><span
id="xiv.iii.lviii-p2.1"></span>It</span> is not right to offer honey and
milk on the altar.

<span id="xiv.iii.lviii-p3"></span><span class="c4"><span
id="xiv.iii.lviii-p3.1"></span>Notes.</span>

<span id="xiv.iii.lviii-p4"></span><span class="sc"><span
id="xiv.iii.lviii-p4.1"></span>Ancient Epitome of Canon LVII.</span>

<span id="xiv.iii.lviii-p5"></span>No one should offer honey or milk at
the altar.

<span id="xiv.iii.lviii-p6"></span>See canon iij. of the Apostles, canon
xxviij. of the African code, also canon xxviij. of this synod.  The
Greeks apparently do not recognize the exception specified in the canon
of the African Code.

